  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="KT17-kilavi">tōḻiyiṟ kūṭṭam vēṇṭip piṉṉiṉṟa talaimakaṉ tōḻi kuṟai maṟāmal kūṟiyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">Uttered so that the confidante might not refuse [his] request by HIM who begged wishing the help of the confidante.</p>
          </div>

        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="KT17">
<l>                māveṉa maṭalu mūrpa pūveṉak</l>
<l>                kuvimuki ḻerukkaṅ kaṇṇiyuñ cūṭupa</l>
<l>                maṟuki ṉārkkavum paṭupa</l>
<l>                piṟitu mākupa kāmaṅkāḻk koḷiṉē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l>For horses they'll ride Palmyra-stems and for flowers</l>
                <l>they'll wear Yarcum chaplets of piled-up buds</l>
                <l>and in the streets they'll happen to shout</l>
                <l>and other things will come forth<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">piṟitum ākupa</term> is a combination of a pronoun in n.sg. as a subject with a 3rd pl. for predicate: this is unusual, but it might be explained as a literary freedom for the sake of the parallelism of the 4 lines.</note> if desire comes to a climax.</l>
                <lg type="alternate" resp="#TVG" sameAs="3b+4b">
                  <l>and in the streets they'll be shouted at<note place="foot">So this means that, they will make themselves a public nuisance – KT 32 in this connection talks about <term xml:lang="ta">paḻi</term> "disgrace". If so, it means taking paṭupa already as a marker of the passive. There are a few passages in the KT where this seems possible (cf. KT 194.1, 288.5).</note></l>
                  <l>and they'll become some other thing ...<note place="foot">So Cām.'s alternative interpretation; for the traditional last escape is jumping off a mountain. (Where this is clearly attested for the first time I do not know, unless in KT 69, where it is the solution chosen by a female monkey who had lost her husband.) A similar suggestive formulation with piṟitu is to be found in KT 69.1, 302.9.</note></l>
                </lg>
                

             </lg>
        </div>
